{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-8939e9dcf5c2f0ea", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tarXiv:2607.13669v1 [cs.CV] 15 Jul 2026\n2\t\n3\tLearning Speaker Identity Beyond Language and Modality\n4\tConstraints: Insights from the POLY-SIM 2026 Challenge\n5\tMarta Moscati∗\n6\t\n7\tMuhammad Saad Saeed∗\n8\t\n9\tMarina Zanoni\n10\t\n11\tInstitute of Computational Perception,\n12\tJohannes Kepler University\n13\tAlbatross AI\n14\tLinz, Austria\n15\tmarta.moscati@jku.at\n16\t\n17\tUniversity of Michigan-Flint\n18\tFlint, United States of America\n19\tmsaads@umich.edu\n20\t\n21\tBDO DIGITAL Gmbh\n22\tDüsseldorf, Germany\n23\tmarina.zanoni@bdo.de\n24\t\n25\tMubashir Noman\n26\t\n27\tRohan Kumar Das\n28\t\n29\tMonorama Swain\n30\t\n31\tMohamed bin Zayed University of\n32\tArtificial Intelligence\n33\tAbu Dhabi, United Arab Emirates\n34\tmubashir.noman@mbzuai.ac.ae\n35\t\n36\tFortemedia\n37\tSingapore, Singapore\n38\trohankd@fortemedia.com\n39\t\n40\tInstitute of Computational Perception,\n41\tJohannes Kepler University\n42\tLinz, Austria\n43\tmonorama.swain@jku.at\n44\t\n45\tYassin Terraf\n46\t\n47\tYufang Hou\n48\t\n49\tElisabeth Andre\n50\t\n51\tCollege of Computing, Mohammed VI\n52\tPolytechnic University\n53\tBenguerir, Morocco\n54\tyassin.terraf@um6p.ma\n55\t\n56\tIT:U Interdisciplinary Transformation\n57\tUniversity\n58\tLinz, Austria\n59\tyufang.hou@it-u.at\n60\t\n61\tUniversity of Augsburg\n62\tAugsburg, Germany\n63\telisabeth.andre@uni-a.de\n64\t\n65\tKhalid Mahmood Malik\n66\t\n67\tMarkus Schedl\n68\t\n69\tShah Nawaz∗†\n70\t\n71\tUniversity of Michigan-Flint\n72\tFlint, United States of America\n73\tdrmalik@umich.edu\n74\t\n75\tInstitute of Computational Perception,\n76\tJohannes Kepler University\n77\tHuman-centered AI Group, AI Lab,\n78\tLinz Institute of Technology, Austria\n79\tLinz, Austria\n80\tmarkus.schedl@jku.at\n81\t\n82\tInstitute of Computational Perception,\n83\tJohannes Kepler University\n84\tLinz, Austria\n85\tshah.nawaz@jku.at\n86\t\n87\tAbstract\n88\tMultimodal speaker identification systems typically assume the\n89\tavailability of complete and homogeneous audio–visual modalities during both training and testing, and assume each speaker\n90\tonly speaks a single language. However, in real-world applications,\n91\tsuch assumptions often do not hold. Visual or audio information\n92\tmay be missing due to occlusions, camera or microphone failures,\n93\tor privacy constraints. Multilingual speakers introduce additional\n94\tcomplexity due to linguistic variability across languages. These\n95\tsituations constitute substantial challenges for the robustness and\n96\tgeneralization capabilities of multimodal speaker identification\n97\t∗ Equal contribution.\n98\t\n99\tsystems. Aim of the POLY-SIM 2026 challenge is to address these aspects of speaker identification and to provide a standardized setup\n100\tfor the comparison of the proposed solutions.\n101\t\n102\tCCS Concepts\n103\t• Computing methodologies → Biometrics; Machine learning.\n104\t\n105\tKeywords\n106\tMultimodal learning, Face-voice association, Missing modality,\n107\tCross linguality\n108\t\n109\t† Corresponding author.\n110\t\n111\tPermission to make digital or hard copies of all or part of this work for personal or\n112\tclassroom use is granted without fee provided that copies are not made or distributed\n113\tfor profit or commercial advantage and that copies bear this notice and the full citation\n114\ton the first page. Copyrights for components of this work owned by others than the\n115\tauthor(s) must be honored. Abstracting with credit is permitted. To copy otherwise, or\n116\trepublish, to post on servers or to redistribute to lists, requires prior specific permission\n117\tand/or a fee. Request permissions from permissions@acm.org.\n118\tMM ’26, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n119\t© 2026 Copyright held by the owner/author(s). Publication rights licensed to ACM.\n120\tACM ISBN 978-x-xxxx-xxxx-x/YYYY/MM\n121\thttps://doi.org/XXXXXXX.XXXXXXX\n122\t\n123\tACM Reference Format:\n124\tMarta Moscati∗ , Muhammad Saad Saeed∗ , Marina Zanoni, Mubashir Noman,\n125\tRohan Kumar Das, Monorama Swain, Yassin Terraf, Yufang Hou, Elisabeth\n126\tAndre, Khalid Mahmood Malik, Markus Schedl, and Shah Nawaz∗† . 2026.\n127\tLearning Speaker Identity Beyond Language and Modality Constraints:\n128\tInsights from the POLY-SIM 2026 Challenge. In Proceedings of the 34th ACM\n129\tInternational Conference on Multimedia (MM ’26), 10–14 November 2026,\n130\tRio de Janeiro, Brazil. ACM, New York, NY, USA, 5 pages. https://doi.org/\n131\tXXXXXXX.XXXXXXX\n132\t\n133\t\fMM ’26, 10–14 November 2026„ Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n134\t\n135\t1\n136\t\n137\tMarta Moscati et al.\n138\t\n139\tIntroduction\n140\t\n141\tThe face and voice of a person have unique characteristics and they\n142\tare often used as biometric measures for speaker identification,\n143\teither individually or combined together as a multimodal input\n144\tsignal [8]. Recent advancements in face-voice association have\n145\tbeen fueled by the curation of large-scale audio-visual datasets\n146\tsuch as VoxCeleb [2, 18, 19] and VoxBlink [13]. These datasets\n147\tenable the development of multimodal models [10, 21, 27–29] for\n148\tspeaker identification. However, a major limitation of existing models, even when trained on multimodal data, is that they require both\n149\tthe audio and the visual modalities to achieve good performance.\n150\tThese models therefore experience performance deterioration if\n151\tevaluated when one of the modalities is not available. This situation, referred to as missing modality, is a well-known challenge\n152\tin multimodal learning across several tasks [1, 5–7, 11, 12, 14, 25].\n153\tA separate challenge, specific to tasks such as speaker identification, is that of language shifts: when trained on one language (e.g.,\n154\tEnglish) and evaluated on another (e.g., German), existing methods experience a performance deterioration, often attributed to the\n155\tacoustic and phonetic differences between the train and evaluation\n156\tlanguages [15, 20, 24]. To foster the development of solutions to\n157\tthese situations, we held the Polyglot Speaker Identification with\n158\tMissing Modality (POLY-SIM) grand challenge, in which participants investigated multimodal learning under missing-modality\n159\tand cross-lingual settings. To mimic a broad set of real-world situations, the challenge consisted of four different evaluation protocols,\n160\tas illustrated in Figure 1. These protocols are designed to evaluate\n161\thow well multimodal models leverage partial inputs and maintain\n162\tstrong cross-lingual speaker identification generalization .\n163\t\n164\t2\n165\t\n166\tThe POLY-SIM Grand Challenge\n167\t\n168\tIn this section we describe the task of the POLY-SIM grand challenge, as well as the training and evaluation data to be used in each\n169\tprotocol as summarized in Figure 1.\n170\t\n171\t2.1\n172\t\n173\tTask Overview\n174\t\n175\tModels developed for the POLY-SIM grand challenge are developed for face-voice association formulated as multimodal speaker\n176\tclassification [15].\n177\t\n178\t2.2\n179\t\n180\tEvaluation Protocol\n181\t\n182\tTraining data consist of paired samples of face images and speech\n183\tsegments. All train speech segments belong to the same language\n184\t(English) for all speakers. At test time, the face modality might be\n185\tmissing, and the available speech segment might be in another language (Urdu). Combinations of these settings result in the different\n186\tevaluation protocols (P) designed for the challenge and simulate\n187\treal-world scenarios including both (i) the missing visual modality\n188\tand (ii) the cross-lingual scenario.\n189\tP3. In-language multimodal. Train and test data consist of\n190\tspeakers speaking the same language (English), and both\n191\tmodalities are available at test time.\n192\tP4. Missing-modality. Train and test data consist of speakers\n193\tspeaking the same language (English). Test data consist of\n194\taudio only, while faces are missing.\n195\t\n196\tTrain\n197\t\n198\t+\n199\t\n200\tModel\n201\tVoice (English)\n202\t\n203\tFace\n204\t\n205\tP3:Inference (InLanguage Multimodal)\n206\t\n207\tP4:Inference (InLanguage Missing-Face)\n208\t\n209\t+\n210\t\n211\t+\n212\tVoice (English)\n213\t\n214\tVoice (English)\n215\t\n216\tFace\n217\tP5:Inference (CrossLingual Multimodal)\n218\t\n219\tP6:Inference (CrossLingual Missing-Face)\n220\t\n221\t+\n222\t\n223\t+\n224\tVoice (Urdu)\n225\t\n226\tVoice (Urdu)\n227\t\n228\tFace\n229\t\n230\tFigure 1: POLY-SIM 2026 evaluation protocol. The top blue\n231\tbox represents the training phase, for which English and\n232\tcomplete (both audio and image) data is used. Each of the\n233\tboxes below represents a different evaluation protocol (P).\n234\t\n235\tP5. Cross-lingual and multimodal. Train data consist of speakers speaking one language (English), while test data consist\n236\tof the same speakers speaking a different language (Urdu).\n237\tBoth modalities are available at test time.\n238\tP6. Cross-lingual and missing-modality. Train data consist\n239\tof speakers speaking one language (English), while test data\n240\tconsist of the same speakers speaking a different language\n241\t(Urdu). Test data consist of audio only, while faces are missing.\n242\t\n243\t2.3\n244\t\n245\tDataset\n246\t\n247\tThe grand challenge is based on the MAV-Celeb dataset [16, 20, 24].\n248\tIt consists of audio-visual samples of several speakers while speaking in interviews, talk shows, and television debates. These audiovisual samples were obtained from YouTube videos. Most importantly for what concerns POLY-SIM, for each speaker, the dataset\n249\tconsists of samples in which the speakers speaks two distinct languages (but only one language in each sample). For the challenge\n250\twe selected the dataset subset consisting of speakers appearing\n251\twhile speaking English and Urdu. We adapted the dataset to the\n252\tmultimodal speaker identification task under missing-modality and\n253\tcross-lingual scenarios by separating train and test data according\n254\tto the protocols described in Section 2.2. Table 1 provides the statistics of the dataset, while Figure 2 shows audio-visual samples from\n255\tthe dataset. The dataset is publicly available and provides raw audio\n256\tand image as well as representations encoded with state-of-the-art\n257\tpretrained architectures.\n258\t\n259\t2.4\n260\t\n261\tBaseline Method & Starter Kit\n262\t\n263\tTo allow participants to compare their approaches with existing\n264\tmethods, we released a pretrained instance of a recent multimodal\n265\t\n266\t\fLearning Speaker Identity Beyond Language and Modality Constraints: Insights from the POLY-SIM 2026 Challenge\n267\t\n268\t2.5\n269\t\n270\tMM ’26, 10–14 November 2026„ Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n271\t\n272\tEvaluation Metric\n273\t\n274\tWe evaluate models’ performance in terms of accuracy on the task of\n275\tspeaker classification. Accuracy is measured in terms of 𝑃-accuracy,\n276\twhich measures the proportion of test pairs for which the system\n277\tcorrectly predicted the matching identity among a set of 𝑃 candidates. 𝑃-accuracy is computed for each of the protocols separately.\n278\tThe overall score is the mean 𝑃-accuracy over all four protocols.\n279\t\n280\t1\n281\t\n282\t2\n283\t\n284\t2.6\n285\t\n286\tEvaluation Plan\n287\t\n288\tComprehensive information regarding the grand challenge, including the challenge timeline, baseline methodology, evaluation protocol and metrics, submission system, and participation rules, is\n289\tprovided in the challenge evaluation plan provided to the participants when the challenge was announced, [17].\n290\t\n291\t3\n292\t\n293\t2.7\n294\t\n295\t4\n296\t\n297\tFigure 2: Audio-visual samples randomly selected from the\n298\tMAV-Celeb dataset [16, 20, 23]. The visual data contains different variations such as pose, lighting condition, and motion.\n299\t(Left) The block shows data of speakers speaking English.\n300\t(Right) The block shows data of the same speakers speaking\n301\tUrdu language.\n302\t\n303\tTable 1: MAV-Celeb dataset statistics for English–Urdu language pair.\n304\tLang. Pair\n305\t\n306\tLang.\n307\t\n308\tEnglish–Urdu\n309\t\n310\tEnglish\n311\tUrdu\n312\t\n313\tTotal Videos\n314\t(Tr./Dev./Eval.)\n315\t262 / 70 / 70\n316\t415 / 70 / 70\n317\t\n318\tSamples\n319\t(Tr./Dev./Eval.)\n320\t4039 / 1290 / 1521\n321\t9304 / 1779 / 1623\n322\t\n323\tmethod for face-voice association [22]. The model consists of a\n324\ttwo-branch architecture, in which each branch takes as input the\n325\tembeddings of one of the two modalities (one branch for faces\n326\tand one branch for voices). The embeddings to be used as input\n327\tto the face-encoding branch are obtained using a well-established\n328\tconvolutional neural network pretrained for facial recognition on a\n329\tlarge-scale dataset [26]. The embeddings to be used as input to the\n330\tvoice-encoding branch are obtained using a well-established audio\n331\tencoding network for speaker recognition [3] and pretrained using\n332\tthe training data of the challenge, consisting only of one language\n333\t(English). The multimodal model further combines the outputs\n334\tof the face and voice branches by means of a fusion module. The\n335\tarchitecture is optimized by means cross-entropy on the multimodal\n336\tembeddings of different speakers and is therefore named Fusion\n337\tand Orthogonal Projection (FOP). We refer the readers to Saeed\n338\tet al. [22] and to the repository of the grand challenge for more\n339\tinformation on baseline method1 .\n340\t\n341\t1 https://github.com/msaadsaeed/polysim\n342\t\n343\tChallenge Timeline and Results\n344\t\n345\tThe challenge consisted of two phases. For both phases, participants were allowed to use only the labels of the English training.\n346\tIn the first phase (March 27, 2026, to May 17, 2026) participants’ approaches were evaluated on a development set, whose labels were\n347\talso available to participants. Each team was allowed to submit 15\n348\tsubmissions per day, with a maximum number of 150 submissions\n349\tduring the entire phase. This phase was meant to give participants\n350\tthe required environment to develop their systems and did not\n351\tcount towards the final challenge results. In the second phase (May\n352\t29, 2026 to June 01, 2026) participants’ approaches were evaluated\n353\ton an unseen evaluation set. Each team was allowed for a maximum of 15 submissions over the whole evaluation phase. Figure 3\n354\tshows the cumulative submission counts per team over the whole\n355\tgrand challenge duration. Table 2 presents the performance of the\n356\ttop-3 teams according to the averaged 𝑃-accuracy in the second\n357\tevaluation phase, as well as the performance of the baseline method\n358\tFOP [22]. The participating teams demonstrated a notable improvement over the baseline method, with the leading team, MaskedFOP [4], achieving an accuracy of 99.89%, a considerable gain from\n359\tthe baseline accuracy of 73.37%. This substantial performance gap\n360\tunderscores the success of the challenge, which led to the development of effective methodologies that advanced the state-of-the-art\n361\tfor multimodal speaker identification under missing modality and\n362\tcross-lingual settings. We attribute the performance gain of all\n363\tteams over the baseline to the following consideration. Although\n364\tnone of the teams used test ground-truth labels (i.e., speakers’ identities) for training the proposed methods, a situation that would\n365\tconstitute a breach of the challenge rules, successful approaches\n366\tutilized test input data to develop unsupervised approaches (e.g.,\n367\tfor clustering). In contrast, the baseline method does not utilize test\n368\tinput features in any way, other than as input at inference time.\n369\t\n370\t3\n371\t\n372\tLessons Learned as Organizers\n373\t\n374\tFrom an organizational perspective, we identified several important\n375\tlessons that may inform the design and execution of future grand\n376\tchallenges.\n377\t1. During the challenge, organizers observed that some participants submitted identical prediction files for the paired\n378\t\n379\t\fMM ’26, 10–14 November 2026„ Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n380\t\n381\tMarta Moscati et al.\n382\t\n383\tFigure 3: Cumulative submission counts per team over the grand challenge duration (March 27 -June 1, 2026). Each line\n384\trepresents the running total of submissions for one of the 18 participating teams, ordered by final cumulative total (highest\n385\tto lowest). Steeper slopes indicate periods of higher submission activity, while plateaus indicate inactivity. A total of 952\n386\tsubmissions were recorded across all teams during the observation window.\n387\tTable 2: Performance in accuracy (%) for English–Urdu cross-lingual experiments.\n388\t\n389\tConfiguration\n390\t\n391\tMethod\n392\t\n393\tFace-Audio (Eng.)\n394\t\n395\tBaseline FOP [22]\n396\tMaskedFOP [4]\n397\tMRAF [9]\n398\tAMR [30]\n399\t\n400\tP3\n401\tFace–Audio (Eng.)\n402\t\n403\tP4\n404\tAudio (Eng.)\n405\t\n406\tP5\n407\tFace–Audio (Urdu)\n408\t\n409\tP6\n410\tAudio (Urdu)\n411\t\n412\tAvg.\n413\t\n414\t98.82\n415\t99.80\n416\t100\n417\t99.93\n418\t\n419\t52.53\n420\t99.80\n421\t98.48\n422\t97.50\n423\t\n424\t98.27\n425\t100\n426\t100\n427\t100\n428\t\n429\t43.87\n430\t99.94\n431\t99.32\n432\t98.83\n433\t\n434\t73.37\n435\t99.89\n436\t99.56\n437\t99.07\n438\t\n439\tsettings P3/P4 and P5/P6. Since P3 and P5 correspond to multimodal evaluation, while P4 and P6 correspond to missingmodality and cross-lingual evaluation, identical submissions\n440\tundermine the intended purpose of the benchmark. Therefore, we introduced an additional validation mechanism to\n441\tensure that submissions for multimodal, missing-modality\n442\tand cross-lingual tracks remained distinct.\n443\t2. While the top-performing approaches successfully handled\n444\tthe grand challenge and achieved impressively accurate predictions, most of them exploited the availability of test-time\n445\tinput data from both source and target languages, i.e., English and Urdu, to develop unsupervised adaptation strategies, such as clustering-based methods. However, assuming\n446\tthat enough representative samples in both languages are\n447\tavailable is restrictive in real-world scenarios, where one\n448\tof the languages is typically less represented, and is hence\n449\t\n450\ttreated as unheard at inference time. Therefore, future research should focus on cross-lingual multimodal methods\n451\tthat generalize to unheard target languages without relying\n452\ton test-time input data for generalization.\n453\t\n454\t4\n455\t\n456\tAcknowledgments\n457\t\n458\tThis research was funded in whole or in part by the Austrian\n459\tScience Fund (FWF): Cluster of Excellence Bilateral Artificial Intelligence (https://doi.org/10.55776/COE12), the doc.funds.connect\n460\tproject Human-Centered Artificial Intelligence (https://doi.org/10.\n461\t55776/DFH23), and the PI project Intent-aware Music Recommender\n462\tSystems (https://doi.org/10.55776/P36413). For open access purposes, the authors have applied a CC BY public copyright license\n463\tto any author-accepted manuscript version arising from this submission.\n464\t\n465\t\fLearning Speaker Identity Beyond Language and Modality Constraints: Insights from the POLY-SIM 2026 Challenge\n466\t\n467\tReferences\n468\t[1] Felix Breiteneder, Mohammad Belal, Muhammad Saad Saeed, Shahed Masoudian,\n469\tUsman Naseem, Kulshrestha Juhi, Markus Schedl, and Shah Nawaz. 2026. Robust\n470\tHarmful Meme Detection under Missing Modalities via Shared Representation\n471\tLearning. In Proceedings of the ACM on Web Conference.\n472\t[2] Joon Son Chung, Arsha Nagrani, and Andrew Zisserman. 2018. VoxCeleb2: Deep\n473\tSpeaker Recognition. In Interspeech 2018. 1086–1090. doi:10.21437/Interspeech.\n474\t2018-1929\n475\t[3] Brecht Desplanques, Jenthe Thienpondt, and Kris Demuynck. 2020. ECAPATDNN: Emphasized Channel Attention, Propagation and Aggregation in TDNN\n476\tBased Speaker Verification. In Interspeech 2020. 3830–3834.\n477\t[4] Ayoub Elkhouzari, Youssef Iraqi, and Loubna Mekouar. 2026. MaskedFOP: Polyglot Speaker Identification under Missing Visual Modality via Cascaded Graph\n478\tLabel Propagation. arXiv preprint arXiv:2606.14321 (2026).\n479\t[5] Christian Ganhör, Marta Moscati, Anna Hausberger, Shah Nawaz, and Markus\n480\tSchedl. 2024. A multimodal single-branch embedding network for recommendation in cold-start and missing modality scenarios. In ACM Conference on Recommender Systems. 380–390.\n481\t[6] Christian Ganhör*, Marta Moscati*, Anna Hausberger, Shah Nawaz, and Markus\n482\tSchedl. 2025. Single-Branch Network Architectures to Close the Modality Gap\n483\tin Multimodal Recommendation. ACM Transactions on Recommender Systems\n484\t(2025).\n485\t[7] Zirun Guo, Tao Jin, and Zhou Zhao. 2024. Multimodal Prompt Learning with\n486\tMissing Modalities for Sentiment Analysis and Emotion Recognition. In Annual\n487\tMeeting of the Association for Computational Linguistics (Volume 1: Long Papers).\n488\t1726–1736.\n489\t[8] Anil K Jain, Arun Ross, and Salil Prabhakar. 2004. An introduction to biometric\n490\trecognition. IEEE Transactions on circuits and systems for video technology 14, 1\n491\t(2004), 4–20.\n492\t[9] Peng Jia, Li Dai, Jia Li, Zhenzhen Hu, Ye Zhao, and Richang Hong. 2026. MissingToken Prompted Reliability-Aware Fusion for Robust Polyglot Speaker Identification. arXiv preprint arXiv:2606.12495 (2026).\n493\t[10] Yidi Jiang, Ruijie Tao, Zexu Pan, and Haizhou Li. 2023. Target Active Speaker\n494\tDetection with Audio-visual Cues. In Interspeech 2023. 3152–3156. doi:10.21437/\n495\tInterspeech.2023-574\n496\t[11] Muhammad Irzam Liaqat, Qaiser Abbas, Shah Nawaz, Zaigham Zaheer, Marta\n497\tMoscati, Yufang Hou, Muhammad Haris Khan, Salman Khan, Elisabeth Andre,\n498\tand Markus Schedl. 2025. Multimodal Learning Under Imperfect Data Conditions:\n499\tA Survey. Authorea Preprints (2025).\n500\t[12] Ronghao Lin and Haifeng Hu. 2023. Missmodal: Increasing robustness to missing\n501\tmodality in multimodal sentiment analysis. Transactions of the Association for\n502\tComputational Linguistics 11 (2023), 1686–1702.\n503\t[13] Yuke Lin, Ming Cheng, Fulin Zhang, Yingying Gao, Shilei Zhang, and Ming\n504\tLi. 2024. VoxBlink2: A 100K+ Speaker Recognition Corpus and the Open-Set\n505\tSpeaker-Identification Benchmark. In Interspeech 2024. 4263–4267. doi:10.21437/\n506\tInterspeech.2024-1490\n507\t[14] Mengmeng Ma, Jian Ren, Long Zhao, Davide Testuggine, and Xi Peng. 2022. Are\n508\tmultimodal transformers robust to missing modality?. In IEEE/CVF conference on\n509\tcomputer vision and pattern recognition. 18177–18186.\n510\t[15] Marta Moscati, Ahmed Abdullah, Muhammad Saad Saeed, Shah Nawaz, Rohan Kumar Das, Muhammad Zaigham Zaheer, Junaid Mir, Muhammad Haroon Yousaf, Khalid Malik, and Markus Schedl. 2025. Face-voice Association in Multilingual Environments (FAME) 2026 Challenge Evaluation Plan.\n511\tarXiv:2508.04592 [cs.CV] https://arxiv.org/abs/2508.04592\n512\t[16] Marta Moscati, Ahmed Abdullah, Muhammad Saad Saeed, Shah Nawaz, Rohan Kumar Das, Muhammad Zaigham Zaheer, Junaid Mir, Muhammad Haroon\n513\tYousaf, Khalid Mahmood Malik, and Markus Schedl. 2026. Linking Faces and\n514\t\n515\tMM ’26, 10–14 November 2026„ Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n516\t\n517\tVoices Across Languages: Insights from the FAME 2026 Challenge. In ICASSP\n518\t2026-2026 IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing\n519\t(ICASSP). IEEE.\n520\t[17] Marta Moscati, Muhammad Saad Saeed, Marina Zanoni, Mubashir Noman, Rohan Kumar Das, Monorama Swain, Yufang Hou, Elisabeth Andre, Khalid Mahmood Malik, Markus Schedl, et al. 2026. POLY-SIM: Polyglot Speaker Identification with Missing Modality Grand Challenge 2026 Evaluation Plan. arXiv\n521\tpreprint arXiv:2603.24569 (2026).\n522\t[18] Arsha Nagrani, Joon Son Chung, Weidi Xie, and Andrew Zisserman. 2020. Voxceleb: Large-scale speaker verification in the wild. Computer Speech & Language\n523\t60 (2020), 101027.\n524\t[19] A. Nagrani, J. S. Chung, and A. Zisserman. 2017. VoxCeleb: a large-scale speaker\n525\tidentification dataset. In Interspeech 2017.\n526\t[20] Shah Nawaz, Muhammad Saad Saeed, Pietro Morerio, Arif Mahmood, Ignazio\n527\tGallo, Muhammad Haroon Yousaf, and Alessio Del Bue. 2021. Cross-modal\n528\tspeaker verification and recognition: A multilingual perspective. In IEEE/CVF\n529\tconference on computer vision and pattern recognition. 1682–1691.\n530\t[21] R Gnana Praveen and Jahangir Alam. 2025. LAVViT: Latent Audio-Visual Vision Transformers for Speaker Verification. In IEEE International Conference on\n531\tAcoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP) 2025. 1–5.\n532\t[22] Muhammad Saad Saeed, Muhammad Haris Khan, Shah Nawaz, Muhammad Haroon Yousaf, and Alessio Del Bue. 2022. Fusion and orthogonal projection for\n533\timproved face-voice association. In IEEE International Conference on Acoustics,\n534\tSpeech and Signal Processing (ICASSP) 2022. 7057–7061.\n535\t[23] Muhammad Saad Saeed, Shah Nawaz, Marta Moscati, Rohan Kumar Das, Muhammad Salman Tahir, Muhammad Zaigham Zaheer, Muhammad Irzam Liaqat,\n536\tMuhammad Haris Khan, Karthik Nandakumar, Muhammad Haroon Yousaf, et al.\n537\t2024. A synopsis of fame 2024 challenge: Associating faces with voices in multilingual environments. In Proceedings of the 32nd ACM International Conference\n538\ton Multimedia. 11333–11334.\n539\t[24] Muhammad Saad Saeed*, Shah Nawaz*, Marta Moscati*, Rohan Kumar Das,\n540\tMuhammad Salman Tahir, Muhammad Zaigham Zaheer, Muhammad Irzam Liaqat, Muhammad Haris Khan, Karthik Nandakumar, Muhammad Haroon Yousaf,\n541\tand Markus Schedl. 2024. A Synopsis of FAME 2024 Challenge: Associating Faces\n542\twith Voices in Multilingual Environments. In ACM International Conference on\n543\tMultimedia (Melbourne VIC, Australia) (MM ’24). Association for Computing\n544\tMachinery, 11333–11334.\n545\t[25] Muhammad Saad Saeed, Shah Nawaz, Muhammad Zaigham Zaheer, Muhammad Haris Khan, Karthik Nandakumar, Muhammad Haroon Yousaf, Hassan\n546\tSajjad, Tom De Schepper, and Markus Schedl. 2024. Modality Invariant Multimodal Learning to Handle Missing Modalities: A Single-Branch Approach. arXiv\n547\tpreprint arXiv:2408.07445 (2024).\n548\t[26] Florian Schroff, Dmitry Kalenichenko, and James Philbin. 2015. Facenet: A unified\n549\tembedding for face recognition and clustering. In IEEE conference on computer\n550\tvision and pattern recognition. 815–823.\n551\t[27] Ruijie Tao, Rohan Kumar Das, and Haizhou Li. 2020. Audio-Visual Speaker\n552\tRecognition with a Cross-Modal Discriminative Network. In Interspeech 2020.\n553\t2242–2246. doi:10.21437/Interspeech.2020-1814\n554\t[28] Ruijie Tao, Zexu Pan, Rohan Kumar Das, Xinyuan Qian, Mike Zheng Shou, and\n555\tHaizhou Li. 2021. Is someone speaking? exploring long-term temporal features\n556\tfor audio-visual active speaker detection. In ACM international conference on\n557\tmultimedia. 3927–3935.\n558\t[29] Yassin Terraf and Youssef Iraqi. 2024. CoMISI: Multimodal Speaker Identification in Diverse Audio-Visual Conditions Through Cross-Modal Interaction. In\n559\tInternational Conference on Neural Information Processing. Springer, 61–77.\n560\t[30] Chuxiao Zuo, Yao Zhu, Minqiang Xu, Manhong Wang, Yunke Zhang, and Fei\n561\tHuang. 2026. AMR: Adaptive Modality Routing for Multimodal Polyglot Speaker\n562\tIdentification. arXiv preprint arXiv:2606.29335 (2026).\n563\t\n564\t\f\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "dfc9b93b-02f3-49e7-a28e-63d98f417879", "uuid": "3d0a03db-da12-4529-a56a-4906aefbf7a3", "timestamp": "2026-07-16T10:04:32.719Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/poly_sim.txt", "content": "arXiv:2607.13669v1 [cs.CV] 15 Jul 2026\n\nLearning Speaker Identity Beyond Language and Modality\nConstraints: Insights from the POLY-SIM 2026 Challenge\nMarta Moscati∗\n\nMuhammad Saad Saeed∗\n\nMarina Zanoni\n\nInstitute of Computational Perception,\nJohannes Kepler University\nAlbatross AI\nLinz, Austria\nmarta.moscati@jku.at\n\nUniversity of Michigan-Flint\nFlint, United States of America\nmsaads@umich.edu\n\nBDO DIGITAL Gmbh\nDüsseldorf, Germany\nmarina.zanoni@bdo.de\n\nMubashir Noman\n\nRohan Kumar Das\n\nMonorama Swain\n\nMohamed bin Zayed University of\nArtificial Intelligence\nAbu Dhabi, United Arab Emirates\nmubashir.noman@mbzuai.ac.ae\n\nFortemedia\nSingapore, Singapore\nrohankd@fortemedia.com\n\nInstitute of Computational Perception,\nJohannes Kepler University\nLinz, Austria\nmonorama.swain@jku.at\n\nYassin Terraf\n\nYufang Hou\n\nElisabeth Andre\n\nCollege of Computing, Mohammed VI\nPolytechnic University\nBenguerir, Morocco\nyassin.terraf@um6p.ma\n\nIT:U Interdisciplinary Transformation\nUniversity\nLinz, Austria\nyufang.hou@it-u.at\n\nUniversity of Augsburg\nAugsburg, Germany\nelisabeth.andre@uni-a.de\n\nKhalid Mahmood Malik\n\nMarkus Schedl\n\nShah Nawaz∗†\n\nUniversity of Michigan-Flint\nFlint, United States of America\ndrmalik@umich.edu\n\nInstitute of Computational Perception,\nJohannes Kepler University\nHuman-centered AI Group, AI Lab,\nLinz Institute of Technology, Austria\nLinz, Austria\nmarkus.schedl@jku.at\n\nInstitute of Computational Perception,\nJohannes Kepler University\nLinz, Austria\nshah.nawaz@jku.at\n\nAbstract\nMultimodal speaker identification systems typically assume the\navailability of complete and homogeneous audio–visual modalities during both training and testing, and assume each speaker\nonly speaks a single language. However, in real-world applications,\nsuch assumptions often do not hold. Visual or audio information\nmay be missing due to occlusions, camera or microphone failures,\nor privacy constraints. Multilingual speakers introduce additional\ncomplexity due to linguistic variability across languages. These\nsituations constitute substantial challenges for the robustness and\ngeneralization capabilities of multimodal speaker identification\n∗ Equal contribution.\n\nsystems. Aim of the POLY-SIM 2026 challenge is to address these aspects of speaker identification and to provide a standardized setup\nfor the comparison of the proposed solutions.\n\nCCS Concepts\n• Computing methodologies → Biometrics; Machine learning.\n\nKeywords\nMultimodal learning, Face-voice association, Missing modality,\nCross linguality\n\n† Corresponding author.\n\nPermission to make digital or hard copies of all or part of this work for personal or\nclassroom use is granted without fee provided that copies are not made or distributed\nfor profit or commercial advantage and that copies bear this notice and the full citation\non the first page. Copyrights for components of this work owned by others than the\nauthor(s) must be honored. Abstracting with credit is permitted. To copy otherwise, or\nrepublish, to post on servers or to redistribute to lists, requires prior specific permission\nand/or a fee. Request permissions from permissions@acm.org.\nMM ’26, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n© 2026 Copyright held by the owner/author(s). Publication rights licensed to ACM.\nACM ISBN 978-x-xxxx-xxxx-x/YYYY/MM\nhttps://doi.org/XXXXXXX.XXXXXXX\n\nACM Reference Format:\nMarta Moscati∗ , Muhammad Saad Saeed∗ , Marina Zanoni, Mubashir Noman,\nRohan Kumar Das, Monorama Swain, Yassin Terraf, Yufang Hou, Elisabeth\nAndre, Khalid Mahmood Malik, Markus Schedl, and Shah Nawaz∗† . 2026.\nLearning Speaker Identity Beyond Language and Modality Constraints:\nInsights from the POLY-SIM 2026 Challenge. In Proceedings of the 34th ACM\nInternational Conference on Multimedia (MM ’26), 10–14 November 2026,\nRio de Janeiro, Brazil. ACM, New York, NY, USA, 5 pages. https://doi.org/\nXXXXXXX.XXXXXXX\n\n\fMM ’26, 10–14 November 2026„ Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n\n1\n\nMarta Moscati et al.\n\nIntroduction\n\nThe face and voice of a person have unique characteristics and they\nare often used as biometric measures for speaker identification,\neither individually or combined together as a multimodal input\nsignal [8]. Recent advancements in face-voice association have\nbeen fueled by the curation of large-scale audio-visual datasets\nsuch as VoxCeleb [2, 18, 19] and VoxBlink [13]. These datasets\nenable the development of multimodal models [10, 21, 27–29] for\nspeaker identification. However, a major limitation of existing models, even when trained on multimodal data, is that they require both\nthe audio and the visual modalities to achieve good performance.\nThese models therefore experience performance deterioration if\nevaluated when one of the modalities is not available. This situation, referred to as missing modality, is a well-known challenge\nin multimodal learning across several tasks [1, 5–7, 11, 12, 14, 25].\nA separate challenge, specific to tasks such as speaker identification, is that of language shifts: when trained on one language (e.g.,\nEnglish) and evaluated on another (e.g., German), existing methods experience a performance deterioration, often attributed to the\nacoustic and phonetic differences between the train and evaluation\nlanguages [15, 20, 24]. To foster the development of solutions to\nthese situations, we held the Polyglot Speaker Identification with\nMissing Modality (POLY-SIM) grand challenge, in which participants investigated multimodal learning under missing-modality\nand cross-lingual settings. To mimic a broad set of real-world situations, the challenge consisted of four different evaluation protocols,\nas illustrated in Figure 1. These protocols are designed to evaluate\nhow well multimodal models leverage partial inputs and maintain\nstrong cross-lingual speaker identification generalization .\n\n2\n\nThe POLY-SIM Grand Challenge\n\nIn this section we describe the task of the POLY-SIM grand challenge, as well as the training and evaluation data to be used in each\nprotocol as summarized in Figure 1.\n\n2.1\n\nTask Overview\n\nModels developed for the POLY-SIM grand challenge are developed for face-voice association formulated as multimodal speaker\nclassification [15].\n\n2.2\n\nEvaluation Protocol\n\nTraining data consist of paired samples of face images and speech\nsegments. All train speech segments belong to the same language\n(English) for all speakers. At test time, the face modality might be\nmissing, and the available speech segment might be in another language (Urdu). Combinations of these settings result in the different\nevaluation protocols (P) designed for the challenge and simulate\nreal-world scenarios including both (i) the missing visual modality\nand (ii) the cross-lingual scenario.\nP3. In-language multimodal. Train and test data consist of\nspeakers speaking the same language (English), and both\nmodalities are available at test time.\nP4. Missing-modality. Train and test data consist of speakers\nspeaking the same language (English). Test data consist of\naudio only, while faces are missing.\n\nTrain\n\n+\n\nModel\nVoice (English)\n\nFace\n\nP3:Inference (InLanguage Multimodal)\n\nP4:Inference (InLanguage Missing-Face)\n\n+\n\n+\nVoice (English)\n\nVoice (English)\n\nFace\nP5:Inference (CrossLingual Multimodal)\n\nP6:Inference (CrossLingual Missing-Face)\n\n+\n\n+\nVoice (Urdu)\n\nVoice (Urdu)\n\nFace\n\nFigure 1: POLY-SIM 2026 evaluation protocol. The top blue\nbox represents the training phase, for which English and\ncomplete (both audio and image) data is used. Each of the\nboxes below represents a different evaluation protocol (P).\n\nP5. Cross-lingual and multimodal. Train data consist of speakers speaking one language (English), while test data consist\nof the same speakers speaking a different language (Urdu).\nBoth modalities are available at test time.\nP6. Cross-lingual and missing-modality. Train data consist\nof speakers speaking one language (English), while test data\nconsist of the same speakers speaking a different language\n(Urdu). Test data consist of audio only, while faces are missing.\n\n2.3\n\nDataset\n\nThe grand challenge is based on the MAV-Celeb dataset [16, 20, 24].\nIt consists of audio-visual samples of several speakers while speaking in interviews, talk shows, and television debates. These audiovisual samples were obtained from YouTube videos. Most importantly for what concerns POLY-SIM, for each speaker, the dataset\nconsists of samples in which the speakers speaks two distinct languages (but only one language in each sample). For the challenge\nwe selected the dataset subset consisting of speakers appearing\nwhile speaking English and Urdu. We adapted the dataset to the\nmultimodal speaker identification task under missing-modality and\ncross-lingual scenarios by separating train and test data according\nto the protocols described in Section 2.2. Table 1 provides the statistics of the dataset, while Figure 2 shows audio-visual samples from\nthe dataset. The dataset is publicly available and provides raw audio\nand image as well as representations encoded with state-of-the-art\npretrained architectures.\n\n2.4\n\nBaseline Method & Starter Kit\n\nTo allow participants to compare their approaches with existing\nmethods, we released a pretrained instance of a recent multimodal\n\n\fLearning Speaker Identity Beyond Language and Modality Constraints: Insights from the POLY-SIM 2026 Challenge\n\n2.5\n\nMM ’26, 10–14 November 2026„ Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n\nEvaluation Metric\n\nWe evaluate models’ performance in terms of accuracy on the task of\nspeaker classification. Accuracy is measured in terms of 𝑃-accuracy,\nwhich measures the proportion of test pairs for which the system\ncorrectly predicted the matching identity among a set of 𝑃 candidates. 𝑃-accuracy is computed for each of the protocols separately.\nThe overall score is the mean 𝑃-accuracy over all four protocols.\n\n1\n\n2\n\n2.6\n\nEvaluation Plan\n\nComprehensive information regarding the grand challenge, including the challenge timeline, baseline methodology, evaluation protocol and metrics, submission system, and participation rules, is\nprovided in the challenge evaluation plan provided to the participants when the challenge was announced, [17].\n\n3\n\n2.7\n\n4\n\nFigure 2: Audio-visual samples randomly selected from the\nMAV-Celeb dataset [16, 20, 23]. The visual data contains different variations such as pose, lighting condition, and motion.\n(Left) The block shows data of speakers speaking English.\n(Right) The block shows data of the same speakers speaking\nUrdu language.\n\nTable 1: MAV-Celeb dataset statistics for English–Urdu language pair.\nLang. Pair\n\nLang.\n\nEnglish–Urdu\n\nEnglish\nUrdu\n\nTotal Videos\n(Tr./Dev./Eval.)\n262 / 70 / 70\n415 / 70 / 70\n\nSamples\n(Tr./Dev./Eval.)\n4039 / 1290 / 1521\n9304 / 1779 / 1623\n\nmethod for face-voice association [22]. The model consists of a\ntwo-branch architecture, in which each branch takes as input the\nembeddings of one of the two modalities (one branch for faces\nand one branch for voices). The embeddings to be used as input\nto the face-encoding branch are obtained using a well-established\nconvolutional neural network pretrained for facial recognition on a\nlarge-scale dataset [26]. The embeddings to be used as input to the\nvoice-encoding branch are obtained using a well-established audio\nencoding network for speaker recognition [3] and pretrained using\nthe training data of the challenge, consisting only of one language\n(English). The multimodal model further combines the outputs\nof the face and voice branches by means of a fusion module. The\narchitecture is optimized by means cross-entropy on the multimodal\nembeddings of different speakers and is therefore named Fusion\nand Orthogonal Projection (FOP). We refer the readers to Saeed\net al. [22] and to the repository of the grand challenge for more\ninformation on baseline method1 .\n\n1 https://github.com/msaadsaeed/polysim\n\nChallenge Timeline and Results\n\nThe challenge consisted of two phases. For both phases, participants were allowed to use only the labels of the English training.\nIn the first phase (March 27, 2026, to May 17, 2026) participants’ approaches were evaluated on a development set, whose labels were\nalso available to participants. Each team was allowed to submit 15\nsubmissions per day, with a maximum number of 150 submissions\nduring the entire phase. This phase was meant to give participants\nthe required environment to develop their systems and did not\ncount towards the final challenge results. In the second phase (May\n29, 2026 to June 01, 2026) participants’ approaches were evaluated\non an unseen evaluation set. Each team was allowed for a maximum of 15 submissions over the whole evaluation phase. Figure 3\nshows the cumulative submission counts per team over the whole\ngrand challenge duration. Table 2 presents the performance of the\ntop-3 teams according to the averaged 𝑃-accuracy in the second\nevaluation phase, as well as the performance of the baseline method\nFOP [22]. The participating teams demonstrated a notable improvement over the baseline method, with the leading team, MaskedFOP [4], achieving an accuracy of 99.89%, a considerable gain from\nthe baseline accuracy of 73.37%. This substantial performance gap\nunderscores the success of the challenge, which led to the development of effective methodologies that advanced the state-of-the-art\nfor multimodal speaker identification under missing modality and\ncross-lingual settings. We attribute the performance gain of all\nteams over the baseline to the following consideration. Although\nnone of the teams used test ground-truth labels (i.e., speakers’ identities) for training the proposed methods, a situation that would\nconstitute a breach of the challenge rules, successful approaches\nutilized test input data to develop unsupervised approaches (e.g.,\nfor clustering). In contrast, the baseline method does not utilize test\ninput features in any way, other than as input at inference time.\n\n3\n\nLessons Learned as Organizers\n\nFrom an organizational perspective, we identified several important\nlessons that may inform the design and execution of future grand\nchallenges.\n1. During the challenge, organizers observed that some participants submitted identical prediction files for the paired\n\n\fMM ’26, 10–14 November 2026„ Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n\nMarta Moscati et al.\n\nFigure 3: Cumulative submission counts per team over the grand challenge duration (March 27 -June 1, 2026). Each line\nrepresents the running total of submissions for one of the 18 participating teams, ordered by final cumulative total (highest\nto lowest). Steeper slopes indicate periods of higher submission activity, while plateaus indicate inactivity. A total of 952\nsubmissions were recorded across all teams during the observation window.\nTable 2: Performance in accuracy (%) for English–Urdu cross-lingual experiments.\n\nConfiguration\n\nMethod\n\nFace-Audio (Eng.)\n\nBaseline FOP [22]\nMaskedFOP [4]\nMRAF [9]\nAMR [30]\n\nP3\nFace–Audio (Eng.)\n\nP4\nAudio (Eng.)\n\nP5\nFace–Audio (Urdu)\n\nP6\nAudio (Urdu)\n\nAvg.\n\n98.82\n99.80\n100\n99.93\n\n52.53\n99.80\n98.48\n97.50\n\n98.27\n100\n100\n100\n\n43.87\n99.94\n99.32\n98.83\n\n73.37\n99.89\n99.56\n99.07\n\nsettings P3/P4 and P5/P6. Since P3 and P5 correspond to multimodal evaluation, while P4 and P6 correspond to missingmodality and cross-lingual evaluation, identical submissions\nundermine the intended purpose of the benchmark. Therefore, we introduced an additional validation mechanism to\nensure that submissions for multimodal, missing-modality\nand cross-lingual tracks remained distinct.\n2. While the top-performing approaches successfully handled\nthe grand challenge and achieved impressively accurate predictions, most of them exploited the availability of test-time\ninput data from both source and target languages, i.e., English and Urdu, to develop unsupervised adaptation strategies, such as clustering-based methods. However, assuming\nthat enough representative samples in both languages are\navailable is restrictive in real-world scenarios, where one\nof the languages is typically less represented, and is hence\n\ntreated as unheard at inference time. Therefore, future research should focus on cross-lingual multimodal methods\nthat generalize to unheard target languages without relying\non test-time input data for generalization.\n\n4\n\nAcknowledgments\n\nThis research was funded in whole or in part by the Austrian\nScience Fund (FWF): Cluster of Excellence Bilateral Artificial Intelligence (https://doi.org/10.55776/COE12), the doc.funds.connect\nproject Human-Centered Artificial Intelligence (https://doi.org/10.\n55776/DFH23), and the PI project Intent-aware Music Recommender\nSystems (https://doi.org/10.55776/P36413). For open access purposes, the authors have applied a CC BY public copyright license\nto any author-accepted manuscript version arising from this submission.\n\n\fLearning Speaker Identity Beyond Language and Modality Constraints: Insights from the POLY-SIM 2026 Challenge\n\nReferences\n[1] Felix Breiteneder, Mohammad Belal, Muhammad Saad Saeed, Shahed Masoudian,\nUsman Naseem, Kulshrestha Juhi, Markus Schedl, and Shah Nawaz. 2026. Robust\nHarmful Meme Detection under Missing Modalities via Shared Representation\nLearning. In Proceedings of the ACM on Web Conference.\n[2] Joon Son Chung, Arsha Nagrani, and Andrew Zisserman. 2018. VoxCeleb2: Deep\nSpeaker Recognition. In Interspeech 2018. 1086–1090. doi:10.21437/Interspeech.\n2018-1929\n[3] Brecht Desplanques, Jenthe Thienpondt, and Kris Demuynck. 2020. ECAPATDNN: Emphasized Channel Attention, Propagation and Aggregation in TDNN\nBased Speaker Verification. In Interspeech 2020. 3830–3834.\n[4] Ayoub Elkhouzari, Youssef Iraqi, and Loubna Mekouar. 2026. MaskedFOP: Polyglot Speaker Identification under Missing Visual Modality via Cascaded Graph\nLabel Propagation. arXiv preprint arXiv:2606.14321 (2026).\n[5] Christian Ganhör, Marta Moscati, Anna Hausberger, Shah Nawaz, and Markus\nSchedl. 2024. A multimodal single-branch embedding network for recommendation in cold-start and missing modality scenarios. In ACM Conference on Recommender Systems. 380–390.\n[6] Christian Ganhör*, Marta Moscati*, Anna Hausberger, Shah Nawaz, and Markus\nSchedl. 2025. Single-Branch Network Architectures to Close the Modality Gap\nin Multimodal Recommendation. ACM Transactions on Recommender Systems\n(2025).\n[7] Zirun Guo, Tao Jin, and Zhou Zhao. 2024. Multimodal Prompt Learning with\nMissing Modalities for Sentiment Analysis and Emotion Recognition. In Annual\nMeeting of the Association for Computational Linguistics (Volume 1: Long Papers).\n1726–1736.\n[8] Anil K Jain, Arun Ross, and Salil Prabhakar. 2004. An introduction to biometric\nrecognition. IEEE Transactions on circuits and systems for video technology 14, 1\n(2004), 4–20.\n[9] Peng Jia, Li Dai, Jia Li, Zhenzhen Hu, Ye Zhao, and Richang Hong. 2026. MissingToken Prompted Reliability-Aware Fusion for Robust Polyglot Speaker Identification. arXiv preprint arXiv:2606.12495 (2026).\n[10] Yidi Jiang, Ruijie Tao, Zexu Pan, and Haizhou Li. 2023. Target Active Speaker\nDetection with Audio-visual Cues. In Interspeech 2023. 3152–3156. doi:10.21437/\nInterspeech.2023-574\n[11] Muhammad Irzam Liaqat, Qaiser Abbas, Shah Nawaz, Zaigham Zaheer, Marta\nMoscati, Yufang Hou, Muhammad Haris Khan, Salman Khan, Elisabeth Andre,\nand Markus Schedl. 2025. Multimodal Learning Under Imperfect Data Conditions:\nA Survey. Authorea Preprints (2025).\n[12] Ronghao Lin and Haifeng Hu. 2023. Missmodal: Increasing robustness to missing\nmodality in multimodal sentiment analysis. Transactions of the Association for\nComputational Linguistics 11 (2023), 1686–1702.\n[13] Yuke Lin, Ming Cheng, Fulin Zhang, Yingying Gao, Shilei Zhang, and Ming\nLi. 2024. VoxBlink2: A 100K+ Speaker Recognition Corpus and the Open-Set\nSpeaker-Identification Benchmark. In Interspeech 2024. 4263–4267. doi:10.21437/\nInterspeech.2024-1490\n[14] Mengmeng Ma, Jian Ren, Long Zhao, Davide Testuggine, and Xi Peng. 2022. Are\nmultimodal transformers robust to missing modality?. In IEEE/CVF conference on\ncomputer vision and pattern recognition. 18177–18186.\n[15] Marta Moscati, Ahmed Abdullah, Muhammad Saad Saeed, Shah Nawaz, Rohan Kumar Das, Muhammad Zaigham Zaheer, Junaid Mir, Muhammad Haroon Yousaf, Khalid Malik, and Markus Schedl. 2025. Face-voice Association in Multilingual Environments (FAME) 2026 Challenge Evaluation Plan.\narXiv:2508.04592 [cs.CV] https://arxiv.org/abs/2508.04592\n[16] Marta Moscati, Ahmed Abdullah, Muhammad Saad Saeed, Shah Nawaz, Rohan Kumar Das, Muhammad Zaigham Zaheer, Junaid Mir, Muhammad Haroon\nYousaf, Khalid Mahmood Malik, and Markus Schedl. 2026. Linking Faces and\n\nMM ’26, 10–14 November 2026„ Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n\nVoices Across Languages: Insights from the FAME 2026 Challenge. In ICASSP\n2026-2026 IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing\n(ICASSP). IEEE.\n[17] Marta Moscati, Muhammad Saad Saeed, Marina Zanoni, Mubashir Noman, Rohan Kumar Das, Monorama Swain, Yufang Hou, Elisabeth Andre, Khalid Mahmood Malik, Markus Schedl, et al. 2026. POLY-SIM: Polyglot Speaker Identification with Missing Modality Grand Challenge 2026 Evaluation Plan. arXiv\npreprint arXiv:2603.24569 (2026).\n[18] Arsha Nagrani, Joon Son Chung, Weidi Xie, and Andrew Zisserman. 2020. Voxceleb: Large-scale speaker verification in the wild. Computer Speech & Language\n60 (2020), 101027.\n[19] A. Nagrani, J. S. Chung, and A. Zisserman. 2017. VoxCeleb: a large-scale speaker\nidentification dataset. In Interspeech 2017.\n[20] Shah Nawaz, Muhammad Saad Saeed, Pietro Morerio, Arif Mahmood, Ignazio\nGallo, Muhammad Haroon Yousaf, and Alessio Del Bue. 2021. Cross-modal\nspeaker verification and recognition: A multilingual perspective. In IEEE/CVF\nconference on computer vision and pattern recognition. 1682–1691.\n[21] R Gnana Praveen and Jahangir Alam. 2025. LAVViT: Latent Audio-Visual Vision Transformers for Speaker Verification. In IEEE International Conference on\nAcoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP) 2025. 1–5.\n[22] Muhammad Saad Saeed, Muhammad Haris Khan, Shah Nawaz, Muhammad Haroon Yousaf, and Alessio Del Bue. 2022. Fusion and orthogonal projection for\nimproved face-voice association. In IEEE International Conference on Acoustics,\nSpeech and Signal Processing (ICASSP) 2022. 7057–7061.\n[23] Muhammad Saad Saeed, Shah Nawaz, Marta Moscati, Rohan Kumar Das, Muhammad Salman Tahir, Muhammad Zaigham Zaheer, Muhammad Irzam Liaqat,\nMuhammad Haris Khan, Karthik Nandakumar, Muhammad Haroon Yousaf, et al.\n2024. A synopsis of fame 2024 challenge: Associating faces with voices in multilingual environments. In Proceedings of the 32nd ACM International Conference\non Multimedia. 11333–11334.\n[24] Muhammad Saad Saeed*, Shah Nawaz*, Marta Moscati*, Rohan Kumar Das,\nMuhammad Salman Tahir, Muhammad Zaigham Zaheer, Muhammad Irzam Liaqat, Muhammad Haris Khan, Karthik Nandakumar, Muhammad Haroon Yousaf,\nand Markus Schedl. 2024. A Synopsis of FAME 2024 Challenge: Associating Faces\nwith Voices in Multilingual Environments. In ACM International Conference on\nMultimedia (Melbourne VIC, Australia) (MM ’24). Association for Computing\nMachinery, 11333–11334.\n[25] Muhammad Saad Saeed, Shah Nawaz, Muhammad Zaigham Zaheer, Muhammad Haris Khan, Karthik Nandakumar, Muhammad Haroon Yousaf, Hassan\nSajjad, Tom De Schepper, and Markus Schedl. 2024. Modality Invariant Multimodal Learning to Handle Missing Modalities: A Single-Branch Approach. arXiv\npreprint arXiv:2408.07445 (2024).\n[26] Florian Schroff, Dmitry Kalenichenko, and James Philbin. 2015. Facenet: A unified\nembedding for face recognition and clustering. In IEEE conference on computer\nvision and pattern recognition. 815–823.\n[27] Ruijie Tao, Rohan Kumar Das, and Haizhou Li. 2020. Audio-Visual Speaker\nRecognition with a Cross-Modal Discriminative Network. In Interspeech 2020.\n2242–2246. doi:10.21437/Interspeech.2020-1814\n[28] Ruijie Tao, Zexu Pan, Rohan Kumar Das, Xinyuan Qian, Mike Zheng Shou, and\nHaizhou Li. 2021. Is someone speaking? exploring long-term temporal features\nfor audio-visual active speaker detection. In ACM international conference on\nmultimedia. 3927–3935.\n[29] Yassin Terraf and Youssef Iraqi. 2024. CoMISI: Multimodal Speaker Identification in Diverse Audio-Visual Conditions Through Cross-Modal Interaction. In\nInternational Conference on Neural Information Processing. Springer, 61–77.\n[30] Chuxiao Zuo, Yao Zhu, Minqiang Xu, Manhong Wang, Yunke Zhang, and Fei\nHuang. 2026. AMR: Adaptive Modality Routing for Multimodal Polyglot Speaker\nIdentification. arXiv preprint arXiv:2606.29335 (2026).\n\n\f", "numLines": 564, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 564}}}
